						<p>Is it possible to have syntax highlighting on screen output, too?</p>
			<br style="clear: both" />
		</div>
<ul class='children'>
		<li class="comment byuser comment-author-jpalardy bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-512">
		<div id="div-comment-512">
		<div class="cmtinfo"><em> on <a href="#comment-512" title="">November 1, 2010 at 6:50 am</a> | <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2007/10/03/like-slime-for-vim/?replytocom=512#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-512", "512", "respond", "53")'>Reply</a></em> <img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ecfd1bdc5d3aab1e40f25658817712ba?s=48&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48' height='48' width='48' /> <cite><a href='http://technotales.wordpress.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Jonathan Palardy</a></cite></div>
						<p>Vim sends a string to the receiver (screen output), it would, consequently, be the responsibility of the receiver to interpret the string and perform highlighting.</p>
<p>Depending on what you&#8217;re trying to do, you can extract Vim&#8217;s syntax highlighting: <a href="http://technotales.wordpress.com/2007/08/11/code-syntax-highlighting-for-blogs-with-vim/" rel="nofollow">http://technotales.wordpress.com/2007/08/11/code-syntax-highlighting-for-blogs-with-vim/</a></p>
			<br style="clear: both" />
		</div>
</li>
